These are the parts I designed for adding a 3rd leadscrew to my 300mm X 300mm D-Bot. I really don't like set screws on my leadscrews, so the parts have the trapezoid thread modeled in and are clamped with m3 hardware. These will only fit 8mm leadscrews with 4-start 2mm pitch threads, which I think are probably the most common anyway.

This is a work in progress! If you have feedback please post in the comments. I think there are advantages to moving the large belt further down, but it will make less room for electronics enclosures and the power supply. I've also been thinking about changing over to a design that captures the leadscrew with a bearing above and below the belt pulley. So far this design has been very functional for me. I printed everything with Inland black PLA @ 215C (higher temp than normal for better inter-layer adhesion)

In this Thing, an Arduino board controls a stepper motor and two leds in series.
The Arduino sketch is based on a NanoV3, but by changing the port numbers, any board can be used. The flash port is connected with the base of an N-FET. 1Watt leds are best, they give nice short flashes and produce a razor sharp image. Adapt the resistor values.
A led holder for 1Watt leds is included. If you see horses running backwards, just swap the leads of one coil of the stepper motor.
Some examples:
https://duckduckgo.com/?q=zoetrope+examples&t=ffsb&iax=1&ia=images
http://thevinylfactory.com/features/the-10-most-mind-bending-vinyl-zoetropes/
The sketch depends on the step angle. Every 36 degrees rotation, the leds should flash

//Stepper
int SA1 = 3; int SA2 = 2; int SB1 = 1;int SB2 = 0;
int F = 4;// flash
int s = 3;//delay between steps
int x = 0;

void setup() {
pinMode(SA1, OUTPUT); pinMode(SA2, OUTPUT);
pinMode(SB1, OUTPUT);pinMode(SB2, OUTPUT);
pinMode(F, OUTPUT);
}
void loop(){
for(x=0;x<20;x++){ //1.8 degrees 2oo steps/rev
digitalWrite(SA1,LOW); digitalWrite(SA2,HIGH); digitalWrite(SB1,HIGH); digitalWrite(SB2,LOW); delay(s);
digitalWrite(SA1,LOW); digitalWrite(SA2,HIGH); digitalWrite(SB1,LOW); digitalWrite(SB2,HIGH); delay(s);
digitalWrite(SA1,HIGH); digitalWrite(SA2,LOW); digitalWrite(SB1,LOW); digitalWrite(SB2,HIGH); delay(s);
digitalWrite(SA1,HIGH); digitalWrite(SA2,LOW); digitalWrite(SB1,HIGH); digitalWrite(SB2,LOW); delay(s);}
digitalWrite(F,HIGH);
delay(1); //short flash
digitalWrite(F,LOW);
}

description.text:
I needed a riser to fit the RMR onto my AR15 and this is what I came up with.
3 slots on a single rail section for RMR, Bushnell trs25, and any other optics or accessories that are too low on their mount.

I've uploaded 3 STLs
First is a whole body print. It will print with a small gap between the clamping piece and will easily come apart. This will result in the best quality print.

Second is the Main Body and Right Side. If your printer isn't tuned well, print them separated and with supports. it is easier to take a file or Dremel and sand down the rough parts than to try to mount something completely out of spec on your weapon.

If you print it, please post photos!
If you enjoy this model, feel free to donate.

description.text:
I bought a Gigabyte Brix computer (i7 4500U) without a case which I plan to dedicate to my 3D Printer. I decided to design and print a case for this computer and i wanted to try printing it in wood filament.

I was running into some issues with the print breaking (not an issue with PLA, but with Wood it was) and lost the source file, so I re-designed the top and base with Wood printing in mind and the fitment is better than before. I have removed all of the old versions of the files leaving the new case parts only. You can view the development and post processing at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WOUzpkdPoZs&feature=youtu.be

I printed the top and bottom in wood filament, I printed the front and back panels in silver PLA, and I printed the power button in clear, and changed the filament 60% through the print to allow the power logo to glow blue through the button. I have not test printed this version of the case fully in plastic, but the print should be a pretty easy print.

  1. Flip the Top Panel Upside down
  2. Insert the Button into the Top Panel
  3. Slide the front panel over the audio Jack on the motherboard and line up the front panel slot in the top panel, slowly lower the motherboard and panel down until its fully seated on the pegs.
  4. Slide in the back panel - it may require a little twisting and bending to get around the plug components - but it fits
  5. align the pegs on the bottom panel and slide it down the pegs - slightly pull out on the sides of the top panel and the bottom should go on far enough that the sides will clip on to the base. No hardware or tools required for the case.
  6. I have not test printed the optional Base - but the completed unit will sit in this base if you choose to use it

description.text:
Parts to create a switch plate, base, and bigger ergonomic knob for the EFI Live CSP switch. supports 4 and 5 positions. The factory knob from a 4x4 selector switch on a 2014-2016 ram 2500 will fit into this nicely and will look stock/from the factory. It will be snug, however glue will keep it in place once you get it operational.

As for placement, it ill require about 1-7/8" hole to be drilled on the drivers side with a little notch for the forward direction. fitment confirmed on 2014, 2015 center consoles. have not been able to check on the newer "round" styles.
There is also a slot for an led to have the tick mark on the factory knob light up. The prewired "little dot SMD accent led" from superbrightled.com will fit into the slot perfectly. hot glue or epoxy can be used to keep it in place.
It is possible to use an led from the circuit board on the donor factory 4x4 selector switch to achieve color matching light. Do not use heat epoxy or glues that cause high heat as it can deform the parts and prevent them from fitting.

To secure the base to the console, i use hot glue this works well for me as i occasionally had been modifying the base and updating the design. The design in now final. (for now)

title: Magnetic Removable Switch Support for Prota MicroBot Push

description.text:
• A magnetic, removable support to be able to use a Prota MicroBot Pushbutton on a switch without permanently fixing it with glue and/or tape.

  • The support can be combined with the button plates for a permanent fix of the button on the (removable) support. Each button comes with three of those plates, but I also designed them to easily be 3D printed.

  • Four magnets need to be glued into the holes of the support, as well as placed behind the plastic plate of the wall power switch (which already has a metallic frame, hence no glue is needed there).

  • See how it works here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HWOVimqCrhA

N.B.

  • The support is made to work with any standard Swiss wall switch: feel free to modify the dimensions to fit your needs!

  • The one you see in the photos has been cut into four pieces to allow some bigger magnets to be inserted instead of the intended ones. Of course one could just reprint it with larger holes... :)

description.text:
After making the top mount hub holders (found here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1752018 ) I didn't like my method of spool hubs. Having a simple plate style hub mount is fine when you work with 1 company for filament, and they don't change the spool design, but what about when you want to switch out to something like a Taulman 910, or a different brand? That's where the progressive hubs come in handy. I looked at several designs and either I didn't like the slop, or the diameter, or the fact that they didn't have an inner bearing, I ended up designing my own.

I'm a fan of overkill so these hubs have a bearing mount on the outside AND the inside. Is it necessary? Not totally, you can just use a hub that doesn't have one, but I already had a few dozen bearings, and since they're not only cheap, they work well, I designed it with inner and outer bearings.

I did notice less drag on this version versus my version without the inner bearing so that sold if for me.

These use standard 8mm X 22mm X 7MM 608ZZ bearings (aka skateboard bearings). They require a bit of pressure to set them in because I didn't want them to come loose.

The holes in the design are simply for cosmetic and to save filament/time.

Also included is a spacer since the 608ZZ bearings are kind of flat, and if you're using larger nuts like I am, the outer ring of the bearing was rubbing on the bolt. I normally have dual filament spools on my top mount system so I use 3 spacers, 1 on the left outer, one in the middle between the spools, and one on the right outer. This setup never snags, almost zero resistance (outside of electrical superconductors, nothing is ZERO resistance on Earth :P)

Thingiverse is a place for sharing, if I don't want to share, I don't post. That being said, as with everything I post, 123D files are available to those who want to modify this. Please feel free to message me and I'll send you the design files.

If you have a Prusa i3, do the combo, it works great.

description.text:
Here is my pinewood derby racer, fresh from several recent wins.

Design:
I notched out the body, and built the back "window" to hold standard 1/4 OZ wheel weights you can buy at harbor freight tool. As it sits it weighs in at an EXACT 5.000 OZ. with a balance point of 1" in front of the rear axle. The wheelbase is a longer than an original drill pinewood derby car (see pictures), but the width and length are the same keeping it within regulation.

I have no wind tunnel tests showing that the rear wing actually does anything, I simply built this car to show the Cub Scouts a modern take on a 100-year-old tradition, and let's be honest, wings look cool.

BUT....I did camber the axle mounts, and design it so the 50/50 balance point is exactly 1" in front of the rear axle.

Build:
I printed it using ABS, but that wasn't necessary, PLA would have been just fine. But what I DID do is I coated my heated bed with goo. I mixed up a thick layer of acetone and abs so that it would create an INSANELY smooth surface on the bottom to assist in aerodynamics. Which is absolutely hilarious because AFTER I printed it I realized I forgot to notch out a weight location on the bottom, so anything the smooth bottom did to help, the low hanging weights ruined. :D

Since I did 0.2mm resolution, it LOOKS like it has grooves at the top that would ruin aerodynamics, but as you can see in the side shots, the top is smooth as glass.

What I learned:
• Don't be in a rush! This was a last minute idea like 2 days before our derby, I forgot to notch out the bottom for weights, could have been more aerodynamic
• Make the axle holes a tiny bit bigger, I made them smaller to make sure they fit tight. The axles fit, but it was a hard press, and you can see the stress on the plastic bottom.
• Redesign top of rails for the rear wing, they fit well, but I think they look a little funny because they're not completely flat to the bottom of the wing. I was looking at my track car when I designed it, and my track car wing is held up by 4 nubs off the wing rails so I designed it the same, looks good on a real car, funny on a pinewood derby car.
• The future design will have small nubs where axles mount to make sure wheels are safely away from the body. They don't rub, but I'd feel better.

Post-Production:
Use acetone to keep the wing together, held up great even after a flying off the track incident.

Results:
Not 1st place but held my own with the top 10 cars. As a parent, I wasn't actually placed, but I would have been in the top 5. I had an alignment issue after it flew off the track so it slowed down dramatically.

Easy build, fun design, I do plan on improving on this.

As always, design files are available to those who'd like to build on this. Entirely designed through 123D so if you don't use that, I can't help you.

description.text:
Hey everyone, I have made a model to commemorate the first landing of the SpaceX Falcon 9 Rocket.

I wanted something to display that would show off this tremendous and inspiring event.
as always if you undertake making one of these and have questions please ask. Most of the purpose for me spending the many many hours to do this is so that others can recreate this work and share in the inspiration and education.

I will do my best to spend time organizing and clarifying things over the next few weeks, but dont wait for it to be perfect to start building yours. I will respond quickly to questions. You will learn the most if you mess up and problem solve. The struggle has always been the source of my learning. I dont want people to get discourraged, but if your uncomfortable it means your growing! just dive in and eff stuff up! My general philosopy is people that want to get good at something usually just mess up enough to eventually have made all the mistakes. Also this project is FAR from perfect so please show off your work! I love seeing it.

I love this stuff so its never a bother to hear from others working on creating.
The files are not quite as organized as I would like, but everything i printed should be here.
I suggest testing the PVC interface parts first with your selected PVC size to figure out a scaling factor for your print, as your material and printer will likely need some tweaking and the parts that interface with the PVC should set the scale for everything else.

I have attempted to upload the instructions I have so far, but please let me know where you have trouble so i can improve and also complete the instructions to make this as easy as possible for anyone to undertake.

as a side note. I made an extra one of these to give to Mr. Musk for providing me so much inspiration. I would love to find a way to get it to him as a thank you. I dont even need to meet him I just want him to have it to do with as he pleases. So if you know how i can make this happen please let me know, it would mean the world to me to get one of these to him.

title: Samsung Galaxy S5 camera screw mount

description.text:
This mount will hold a Samsung Galaxy S5. The phone fits quite tight, so it will not slip out too easy.

The mount hole is threaded with 3/8-16, so an adapter screw will be very easy to fit.

There is a "cut out" to be able to fit a usb charging cable.

The "washer" stl is to be fitted under the mount to fill out for an adapter screw that is longer than what the mount is thick (fit between the actually camera screw support plate and this mount).

Hardware needed:
1/4 => 3/8 screw adapter like the one in one of the attach pictures.

Of course you need some hardware to attach the mount to. There is a lot of options for this. Tripods, bicycle mounts, GoPro mounts and other standard camera mounts. I use the mount to attach my S5 to my MC.

description.text:
A Tardis coffee stirrer

So you are a sweet guy who likes his coffee with some sugar but your brand new Dr. Who cup has that nice Tardis inside which might get damaged by a metal spoon when stirring. Now you can do two things:

  • drink your coffee in two layers - the black one first and the sweet one last
  • print your own fancy Tardis coffee stirrer

This stirrer was modeled in Sketchup, sliced with Craftware (scale to a length of 12cm) and printed with a Geeetech Prusa I3 and PLA.

NOTE ON PLA Do no leave your stirrer for a long time in hot coffee. It might follow gravity adapt in time to some other relative dimension in space.
